x4freetext: Pd-300 Neutron Generator
Fourteen mega electron volt neutron flux was
generated using the T(d,n)4He reaction induced by
the 135 keV deuteron beam energy and 200 uA beam
current.
A calibrated GEM-60P coaxial HPGe detector
(72.3 mm long and 70.1 mm in diameter) was used to
measure the gamma-ray activities of 89mZr, 89gZr,
95mNb, 95gNb and 24Na nuclei after the samples decay
for 5~1800 min. The relative efficiency and energy
resolution of the HPGe detector were 68% and 1.69 keV
(at 1.332 MeV), respectively. The efficiency of the
detector was pre-calibrated using various standard
gamma sources, which were 57Co, 60Co, 109Cd, 133Ba,
137Cs, 152Eu, 241Am and 226Ra. The uncertainty in the
efficiency curve was estimated to be about 3%, while
the uncertainty of the activity of the standard
source is about 2.5-3.0%.
The neutron flux during the irradiation was
monitored by counting alpha particles using Au-Si
surface barrier detector positioned at a 135 degree
angle to correct for the neutron flux variations.
Three Mo foil circles (99.99% purity, 0.5 mm thick
and 20 mm in diameter), each of which was placed
between two Al foil circles (99.999% purity, 0.3 mm
thick and 20 mm in diameter). A stack of Al-Mo-Al
was assembled and wrapped in a cadmium foil in order
to reduce the contribution of thermal and epithermal
effects.
Three samples were positioned at 0, 90, and
135 degree angles with regards to the beam and 5 cm
away from the T-Ti target, irradiated for 2 h, during
which the total yield was about 3E10~4E10 n/s.
The activity correction factor F can be expressed as
F=fg*fs, where fg and fs are correction factors at a
certain counting geometry and gamma-ray
self-absorption, respectively.

uncertainties associated with the calculations of the
following.
